# 7. 前に進めるように

Saito: Shizuku...?
Saito: Is something wrong?
Rin: <Is Shizuku gonna be okay...?>
Airi: Don't worry.
Airi: She always shines in these situations!
Haruka: I agree.
MEIKO: <We should sit back and let her do her thing.>
MEIKO: <Let's see if Shizuku can get through to her...>
Shizuku: There's something I need to tell you.
Shizuku: Regarding your dream...
Saito: ...!
Saito: No, I already said...
Shizuku: Please, just give me a moment to explain. It's important.
Saito: Shizuku...
Shizuku: Your grandmother told me everything.
Shizuku: And she believes that you pursuing your real dream would be the happiest solution.
Saito: But...
Shizuku: After hearing that, I...
Shizuku: I thought that it's okay for you to be more honest about how you feel and what you want.
Shizuku: It's okay for you to want to pursue your dream of supporting idols for a living.
Saito: *Wince*
Saito: I know. My grandma, mom and dad all want me to be happy more than anything else.
Saito: But...
Saito: I have a responsibility. I have to take over running this inn! Because if I don't...!
Shizuku: Yes, I understand how you feel.
Shizuku: I went through something very similar when I was still with Cheerful * Days.
Saito: Oh...
Shizuku: Unfortunately, as you know, things didn't turn out so well for me back then.
Shizuku: There are multiple reasons as to why...
Shizuku: But one had to do with this compulsion to fulfill my responsibilities and not disappoint those around me.
Shizuku: So...
Shizuku: Unlike those who truly love being idols and work hard every day because they don't want to be anything else, I ended up reaching my limit.
Saito: Shizuku...
Shizuku: So, if you're going through what I did... If you're only doing this out of an overwhelming sense of responsibility, I want you to stop and take a step back.
Shizuku: Then, you should ask yourself, “Is this really the path I want to go down?” and, “Will I truly be happy if I do?”
Shizuku: I believe you should have a discussion with those around you and take some time to think before reaching a decision.
Shizuku: Because I live with regret, and I wonder if things might have turned out better had I made better decisions...
Saito: Yes, you might be right.
Shizuku: Saito...
Saito: I know what you're trying to say, Shizuku... Or rather, I realize it now after hearing what you have to say.
Saito: I do feel an overwhelming sense of responsibility to take over this inn and keep it running.
Saito: And I know that if I only have that for motivation... Something will probably go wrong down the line.
Shizuku: Then...
Saito: Even so, I can't let this inn go out of business.
Shizuku: ...!
Saito: I want to become your manager really... I want to make my dream come true by supporting you and the others forever and ever.
Saito: But this inn means just as much to me.
Saito: It isn't precious to just me and my family. It also has a special place in the hearts of our guests.
Saito: What... What right do I have robbing this place from them by acting so childishly?
Senior Proprietress: That isn't acting childishly.
Saito: Grandma...?! Mom...?! Were you both listening just now...?!
Minori: Oh, is that Saito's...?
Rin: <She seems really nice. Just like her mom.>
Senior Proprietress: Let me get this straight. Are you saying that it's “childish” for someone to want to pursue what they want?
Senior Proprietress: You're wrong about that. You aren't being childish.
Senior Proprietress: We're talking about your dream here.
Saito: So...
Saito: So what? That doesn't change anything. I'm still going to take over the inn...
Senior Proprietress: If you're feeling that conflicted, I can't let you take over.
Saito: ...!
Senior Proprietress: What Ms. Hinomori here just said is correct. You won't be able to run this place just because you feel compelled to and don't want to disappoint others.
Senior Proprietress: This inn succeeds only when you strive to do what's best for it and its guests. That feeling needs to be genuine.
Saito: But...
Saito: But I do genuinely believe that! I want what's best for both this inn and its guests!
Saito: That's why I'm so torn! I wouldn't be doing this right now if I didn't feel that way!
Senior Proprietress: So you're “torn”? Does that mean you haven't been able to fully give up on your dream?
Saito: ...! No, I...
Proprietress: Ayaka. Please stop robbing yourself of your dream.
Saito: Mom...
Proprietress: I'm sorry, but your grandmother explained to me what's been going on.
Proprietress: I feel terrible about us placing such high expectations on you. We didn't realize that it would lead to you being forced down this one path.
Proprietress: But you should do what you want. I don't want you to take over if it means giving up on your dream.
Saito: That doesn't make my choice any easier.
Saito: If I don't take over, then this inn that so many people love is gonna disappear.
Saito: I... I don't want that to...
Proprietress: This inn doesn't need to keep running if it takes robbing others of their happiness to do so.
Saito: What...?
Senior Proprietress: She's right. Ryusuiso is meant to be a place that's meant to bring happiness to all.
Senior Proprietress: And not just the guests... Everyone who works here, too. Including you.
Saito: Including me...?
Proprietress: Plus, I'm not about to quit just yet, so there's no immediate need for anyone else to take over. We have time to start looking for someone.
Proprietress: There's no rule saying that a family member has to take over. We can always see if we can hand it over to someone else.
Senior Proprietress: Just so you know, we're not as shortsighted as you think we are.
Senior Proprietress: If you have a dream that you really want to pursue, then you should be doing everything you can to make it come true.
Saito: Mom, Grandma...
Shizuku: What a wonderful family...
Shizuku: You all care so deeply about one another... That certainly explains why this inn feels so warm and welcoming. It's an expression of the Saito family's love and affection.
Saito: Shizuku...
Shizuku: All that's left is for you to make your decision, Saito. But...
Shizuku: I hope you choose a path that you won't regret taking.
Saito: I... I just wanted to protect this inn...
Saito: But... If it doesn't have to be me... If I have the option of choosing my own path...
Saito: Then... I... I want to help idols for a living.
Saito: I want to put on events like the one where I met Shizuku for the first time. I want to put smiles on everyone's faces!
Saito: Mom, Grandma, I'm really sorry...!
Senior Proprietress: Go... However, now you've made your decision, you can't come crawling back. You shouldn't think of us as your safety net. We want you to commit to your dream.
Senior Proprietress: But I think you have what it takes to make it come true, Ayaka. After all, you always put so much effort into the things you love most.
Proprietress: You have our support. Go after what will let you be yourself and shine.
Saito: I will.
Saito: Thank you...!
Shizuku: (Thank goodness Saito changed her mind.)
Shizuku: (Even now, I still wish that things could've gone better for me back then...)
Shizuku: (But, if I was able to convince Saito thanks to having gone through that experience, then...)
Shizuku: (I think I've taken a step forward...)
